# Memoria Engineering Standards

- Prefer deterministic behavior over implicit magic; avoid hidden side effects in UI and command handlers.
- Keep user-visible operations non-destructive by default and preserve auditability when state changes.

## React + TypeScript (`src/**`)

- Use strict typing end-to-end; avoid `any` and keep DTO keys aligned with backend camelCase contracts.
- Add stable `data-testid` attributes for interactive UI controls and stateful cards used in E2E tests.
- Use accessible labels (`label` + `htmlFor`) for all form inputs; do not rely only on placeholders.
- Guard async UI actions with clear status messaging and disable controls while busy.

## Tauri + Rust (`src-tauri/**`)

- Keep command handlers thin; move business logic into `services/*`.
- For schema changes, always implement safe migrations for existing DBs (add columns/indexes idempotently).
- Return structured errors/messages suitable for frontend display; avoid panics in runtime command paths.
- Preserve local/offline fallbacks for AI-dependent flows so core pipeline remains testable.

## SQLite + Fixtures

- Ensure fixture seeding creates both DB rows and real media files when UI paths depend on file rendering.
- Keep fixture profiles explicit (`review-duplicates`, `date-approval`, etc.) and deterministic across runs.

## Playwright UI Testing (`tests/ui/**`)

- Cover critical flows by UI behavior: dashboard pipeline, review actions, duplicate/lightbox flow, date approval, event groups, settings.
- Prefer deterministic seeded fixtures for assertions; use full pipeline only for limited smoke scenarios.
- For desktop tests, isolate app state using test-specific app directories and explicit environment configuration.
- Treat flaky/implicit waits as bugs; assert on stable selectors and explicit state transitions.

## CI Quality Gates

- Required checks should include lint/typecheck, Rust tests, browser UI tests, and desktop UI tests.
- Always upload Playwright artifacts (trace/screenshots/videos) on failure for diagnosis.
